    "Problem Formalization": "The 1D wave equation ∂²u/∂t² = c²∂²u/∂x² governs the field u(x,t). Known quantities: wave speed c, sensor positions S = {x₁,…,xₙ}, and measurements u(xᵢ,t) for t ∈ [0,T]. Unknown and explicitly missing: initial displacement u₀(x), initial velocity v₀(x), and boundary conditions at any domain edges. The solution decomposes into right-going and left-going characteristic components: u(x,t) = f(x−ct) + g(x+ct). A single sensor measurement u(xᵢ,t) = f(xᵢ−ct) + g(xᵢ+ct) provides one equation coupling two unknowns (f and g), so individual wave components cannot be separated from one sensor alone. Recoverability of u(x*,t*) requires that both characteristic values f(x*−ct*) and g(x*+ct*) be individually determinable from the sensor data system. The spatial domain extent is not specified; if finite, boundary reflections depend on unknown BCs and cannot be modeled. We assume the domain is effectively unbounded or that T is small enough that no boundary-reflected characteristic reaches any sensor.",
    "Physics Constraints": "1. PDE residual: u_tt − c²u_xx = 0 everywhere in the space-time domain. 2. Finite propagation speed c: the domain of dependence of (x*,t*) is the characteristic diamond with vertices (x*±ct*, 0) and (x*,t*). 3. Right-going characteristics carry f along lines x−ct = const; left-going characteristics carry g along lines x+ct = const. 4. No initial-condition constraint is imposed (u₀, v₀ are unknown). 5. No boundary-condition constraint is imposed (BCs are unknown). 6. Data consistency: the model must exactly satisfy u(xᵢ,t) = measured value at every sensor point (xᵢ,t). 7. Superposition: u = f + g, and f, g are each constant along their respective characteristic families.",
    "Model Choice": "A two-phase approach combining (1) a deterministic characteristic-geometric analysis with (2) a Physics-Informed Neural Network (PINN) restricted to the recoverable subdomain. Phase 1 is purely geometric and requires no training. Phase 2 uses a PINN with Fourier-feature embeddings (to mitigate spectral bias on wave-type solutions) that parameterizes u(x,t) via two sub-networks for f(ξ) and g(η), composed as u = f(x−ct) + g(x+ct). This factorization enforces the characteristic structure by construction and makes the separation of f and g explicit. The PINN is only evaluated and collocated within the region deemed recoverable by Phase 1. No IC or BC loss terms appear in the objective. An ensemble of independently initialized PINNs identifies regions of non-uniqueness through inter-ensemble variance.",
    "Training Strategy": "Phase 1 — Characteristic coverage analysis: For each sensor xᵢ, compute right-going coverage C_R(i) = [xᵢ−cT, xᵢ] and left-going coverage C_L(i) = [xᵢ, xᵢ+cT]. A point (x*,t*) passes the necessary test if x*−ct* ∈ ∪ᵢ C_R(i) AND x*+ct* ∈ ∪ᵢ C_L(i). For sufficiency, check whether adjacent sensor pairs (xᵢ, xᵢ₊₁) satisfy dᵢ = xᵢ₊₁−xᵢ ≤ cT; if so, time-shifted differencing of their measurements yields g(ξ+2dᵢ)−g(ξ) and f(η−2dᵢ)−f(η), enabling separation of f and g (up to a shared additive constant that cancels in u). The recoverable region R is the set of (x,t) where both characteristics are covered AND at least one sensor pair with dᵢ ≤ cT provides overlapping coverage for those characteristic arguments. Phase 2 — PINN training: Loss = λ_data · L_data + λ_pde · L_pde, where L_data = Σᵢ ∫₀ᵀ |u_θ(xᵢ,t) − u_meas(xᵢ,t)|² dt and L_pde = average |∂²u_θ/∂t² − c²∂²u_θ/∂x²|² over collocation points sampled densely in R. No IC or BC loss terms are included. Collocation points are sampled only in R; points outside R are excluded. An ensemble of K ≥ 5 independently initialized networks is trained. Optimization uses Adam with learning rate 1e-3 for 50k steps, then L-BFGS refinement. Gradient penalties or causal weighting (time-ordered loss) stabilize training for the oscillatory wave solution.",
    "Validation Failure Risks": "1. Non-uniqueness in underdetermined regions: even within R, if sensor spacing is barely sufficient, f and g may be determined only up to a slowly varying ambiguity, causing ensemble variance that is hard to distinguish from optimization failure. Mitigation: report inter-ensemble standard deviation as an epistemic uncertainty map. 2. Incorrect recoverable-region boundary: if the domain is finite and unknown BCs generate reflections that reach sensors within [0,T], the characteristic analysis assumes no reflections and will mischaracterize R. Mitigation: flag any sensor measurement showing wavefront arrivals inconsistent with pure right/left propagation as evidence of boundary reflection, and shrink R accordingly. 3. PINN spectral bias: wave solutions are oscillatory and PINNs may fail to fit high-frequency content. Mitigation: Fourier-feature input encoding with frequency scale matched to expected wave content. 4. Sensor gap too large: if max(dᵢ) > cT for all adjacent pairs, no characteristic overlap exists and the entire field is unrecoverable; the workflow must detect this in Phase 1 and report that only the measured sensor trajectories are constrained. 5. Additive constant ambiguity: u is determined up to a global constant when only differences of f and g are available; the workflow reports this as an irreducible one-parameter family of solutions and fixes the constant by convention (e.g., zero-mean over sensor data). 6. For regions outside R, the workflow explicitly reports 'unconstrained' with no predicted value, rather than extrapolating the PINN output."
