    "Model Choice": "Use a weak-form physics-informed neural network (wPINN) with domain decomposition (e.g., XPINN or hp-VPINN architecture). Justification: (1) Strong-form PINNs fail at discontinuities because PDE residuals are undefined — the weak/integral form averages over test functions and remains well-defined. (2) Domain decomposition allows separate subnetworks per smooth region separated by detected interfaces, preventing cross-discontinuity gradient contamination. (3) The network parameterizes conservative variables U(x,t) with a softplus output transform and learned shift/scale to enforce ρ>0 and p>0. (4) An auxiliary network predicts shock/interface locations parameterically, enabling sharp transitions. Alternative considered: standard PINN (rejected due to Gibbs phenomena at shocks), FNO (rejected if no training data available — data regime unspecified). If simulation data is available, a hybrid wPINN + data loss approach is preferred.",
    "Training Strategy": "(1) Loss components: (a) Weak-form residual loss — integrate conservation laws against compactly-supported test functions over subdomains via quadrature; (b) Entropy residual loss — penalize ∂(ρs)/∂t + ∂(ρus)/∂x < 0 violations (s = specific entropy) to enforce entropy inequality; (c) Rankine-Hugoniot loss at predicted shock interfaces; (d) Initial condition loss on piecewise states; (e) Boundary condition loss (once specified); (f) Positivity penalty on ρ and p. (2) Sampling: space-time collocation with adaptive refinement — densify sampling near predicted shock curves and contact discontinuities using residual-based error indicators; re-sample every N epochs. (3) Optimization: Adam with learning rate scheduling, followed by L-BFGS fine-tuning in smooth subdomains only. (4) Causal/time-marching training: train on early time windows first, progressively extending, to avoid temporal shortcut failures. (5) Adaptive loss weighting using GradNorm or learned uncertainty weights to balance competing objectives. (6) Curriculum: start with viscous regularization (add small artificial viscosity ν), anneal ν → 0 during training to stabilize early optimization while converging to inviscid solution.",
