    "Problem Formalization": "The governing PDE is the steady-state Darcy equation: -∇·(K(x)∇h(x)) = f(x) on domain Ω ⊂ ℝ^d, where h is hydraulic head, K(x) is the spatially varying high-contrast permeability field containing fine-scale channels (K_channel >> K_background, contrast ratios potentially 10^3–10^6), and f is the source term. Boundary conditions (Dirichlet and/or Neumann) and f are stated as available but their specific types and values are not given. Missing specifications: (1) domain geometry and dimensionality (2D vs 3D critically affects cost), (2) boundary condition types and values on each boundary segment, (3) contrast ratio and channel geometry statistics (width, connectivity, orientation), (4) whether K fields are parameterized (e.g., via Karhunen-Loève expansion or generative model) or provided as raw grids, (5) required accuracy tolerance, (6) number and diversity of query realizations. The decision between single-instance solver vs. reusable surrogate hinges on items (4)–(6): if many K-realizations from a known distribution must be solved, a learned operator surrogate amortizes training cost; if one or very few difficult fields are needed, a dedicated solver avoids generalization overhead and can exploit field-specific structure.",
