    "Training Strategy": "The total loss is L = L_PDE + L_BC + L_interface + L_continuity, where: (1) L_PDE = Σ_i (1/N_i) Σ_{k=1}^{N_i} |K_i∇²h_i(x_k)|² sampled uniformly within each subdomain Ω_i (strong-form residual valid inside each subdomain where K is constant); (2) L_BC enforces Dirichlet/Neumann conditions on ∂Ω; (3) L_interface = (1/N_Γ) Σ_{j=1}^{N_Γ} [|h₁(x_j) − h₂(x_j)|² + λ|K₁∂h₁/∂n(x_j) − K₂∂h₂/∂n(x_j)|²] sampled on interface points, enforcing head continuity and flux continuity; (4) optionally, a weak-form loss L_weak = |∫_Ω K∇h·∇v dΩ − boundary_terms|² using Monte Carlo integration with test functions v chosen as piecewise polynomial or sinusoidal bases. Sampling strategy: dense collocation near interfaces (refined sampling within a band of width ~0.05·L around Γ_int) to resolve the gradient jump, plus uniform sampling in the bulk. The interface loss weight λ is tuned so that flux continuity and head continuity are balanced. Optimization: Adam with learning rate 1e-3 for 10k steps, then L-BFGS for fine convergence. Gradient penalty or causal weighting is not needed, but the loss weights for interface terms should be progressively increased (curriculum) to first satisfy the PDE in each subdomain, then enforce coupling.",
